<p>The tone and phrasing of your condolence message should be respectful and comforting. Avoid overly formal language or platitudes that may feel dismissive. Instead, focus on sharing your personal memories of the deceased if you have them, and offer practical support if appropriate. Remember, your presence and empathy are valuable gifts in themselves.  The aim is to provide comfort and strength, allowing the bereaved to process their grief at their own pace.</p>
    

